## 🤖 ML Model

### Dataset
- **Source**: [Kaggle Credit Card Fraud Detection](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/mlg-ulb/creditcardfraud)
- **Size**: 284,807 transactions
- **Fraud rate**: 0.173% (highly imbalanced)
- **Features**: 30 (Time, Amount, V1-V28 PCA features)

### Model Performance

| Metric        | Score  |
|---------------|--------|
| AUC-ROC       | 0.9782 |
| Precision     | 0.87   |
| Recall        | 0.82   |
| F1-Score      | 0.84   |

### Key Design Decisions

**Why XGBoost?**
- Best performance on tabular data
- Handles class imbalance via `scale_pos_weight`
- Fast inference (critical for streaming)

**Why Recall over Precision?**
- Missing real fraud > falsely flagging legit
- Better to investigate a false alarm
- than miss an actual fraud

**Why micro-batching over true streaming?**
- XGBoost not natively distributed
- Batch inference is more efficient
- 5-second latency acceptable for fraud detection

---

## 📈 Performance

```
Measured on MacBook Pro M1 (8GB RAM):

Throughput:
→ Producer:  ~100 transactions/second
→ Spark:     ~500 transactions/batch (every 5 sec)

Latency:
→ Kafka ingestion:    <5ms per message
→ Spark micro-batch:  5 seconds trigger
→ ML inference:       ~50ms per batch
→ DB write:           ~100ms per batch
→ End-to-end:         ~5-6 seconds

Accuracy:
→ AUC-ROC:  0.9782
→ Recall:   82% of fraud cases caught
→ FPR:      0.02% false positive rate
```

